definition.value: Organic heterobicyclic compounds containing a two furan rings ortho-fused to each other.
A cephalosporin bearing (1-methylpyrrolidinium-1-yl)methyl and (2Z)-2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetamido groups at positions 3 and 7, respectively, of the cephem skeleton.
Anything used in a scientific experiment to indicate the presence of a substance or quality, change in a body, etc.
A phospho sugar that is formally obtained from a hexose.
Any steroid substituted by at least one carboxy group.
Organic derivatives of sulfonic acid in which the sulfo group is linked directly to carbon of an alkyl group.
An alkanethiol is a compound in which a sulfanyl group, -SH, is attached to an alkyl group.
A prenylcysteine where the prenyl moiety is attached to the side-chain sulfur atom of L-cysteine.

Any member of the 'superclass' flavonoids whose skeleton is based on 1-benzopyran with an aryl substituent at position 2. The term was originally restricted to natural products, but is now also used to describe semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds.
A 2-coumarate that is the conjugate base of cis-2-coumaric acid.
Any molecule that contains three amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.
A monohydroxycinnamic acid in which the hydroxy substituent is located at C-3 of the phenyl ring.
The cis-stereoisomer of 3-coumaric acid.
A 3-coumarate that is the conjugate base of trans-3-coumaric acid.
A D-galactopyranuronic acid with a beta-configuration at the anomeric center.
A D-glucosamine whose structure comprises D-glucopyranose having an amino substituent at position 2.

A monocarboxylic acid amide that is N,N-diethylprop-2-enamide in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a cyano group and the hydrogen at the 3E position is substituted by a 3,4-dihydroxy-5-nitrophenyl group.
An aspartic acid derivative having a 3-methyl substituent.
Ethers ROR' where R has a double bond adjacent to the oxygen of the ether linkage.
The pyranose form of D-glucosamine 6-phosphate.
An amine RNR'R'' where R has a double bond adjacent to the amine nitrogen.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-tryptophan at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-tryptophan by a heteroatom.
Any molecule that contains four amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.
A metabolite from Penicillium brefeldianum that exhibits a wide range of antibiotic activity.
Polypeptides synthesized by specific strains of bacteria that are lethal against other strains of the same or related species.
